column60: I'm not thrilled with the changes to the system.  I appreciated the flexibility of being able to set my own due date and now they're set.  It also seems like it's going to be much harder to earn bonus points now - especially that old great September incentive.  A teacher at school who was saving points for something specific said the store's been revamped and she was disappointed with the choices.  I hope I get used to the site, but flexibility and bonus points were a huge reason why I use Scholastic Book Clubs.  If I am going to purchase gift books for my kids because either I don't have enough bonus points or because of favorite titles not available any more (How Full is your Bucket for Kids, Kevin Henkes, The Gruffalo, My Father's Dragon, and more) I will spend my money at a local bookstore.  I'm glad you're soliciting input and hope the changes end up being positive.

column60: As a teacher, I am extremely disappointed and frustrated by all the changes to Scholastic Book Clubs this year. All the things I loved have been taken away: no 10,000 bonus points, no MacBooks or gift cards in the bonus catalog, no $1 books, no Golden Apple Teacher benefits, no monthly/themed flyers, no flexible due dates. Despite having a low teacher salary, I have invested hundreds of dollars of my own money on Scholastic orders over the years to earn bonus points so that I could save up toward a MacBook Air. Now Scholastic has taken that away and all that money I spent has been wasted. I keep checking the site, hoping that Scholastic will reinstate these things, but continue to be disappointed and frustrated by Scholastic.

column60: The price of the books has increased so much! I'd like to see some of the lower priced books return to the flyers. Even it was a few every month, that would help.    Bonus Point Catalog--Please bring back some of the higher quality bonus points catalog items, such as the electronics and gift cards. These items are really missed. The new bonus point catalog is very poor when compared to previous years. I wish I would have used my many, many points previously, rather than holding on to them. Many people have been saving their points to use towards the higher end items, and now they are gone. I am very disappointed.     I have placed a monthly order for years. It has been great for the students, but it was also an incentive for me to get the points. Now that those higher end items are not offered, I don't know that I will go through the hassle of managing monthly book orders. It may not be worth my time. Please consider bringing them back.

column60: I have been a teacher for 10 years and have been a member of Scholastic Book Clubs since I began. For the last 5 years, I have fundraised to be able to provide my students with a book every month  and birthday coupons. I have raised thousands of dollars to be able to put books into my students hands and I have spent all of that money with you. This year, I raised what should be more than enough money to provide my students with books, but I cannot afford to purchase more than 4 books for each student this year. I understand that inflation is unavoidable, but the prices have skyrocketed. There are no longer dollar books, the dollar book bonus store, birthday coupons, nor are there quality value packs for a reasonable price. The $2 book of the month has also been the same for the last 6 weeks. Again, I understand that a price hike was necessary, but this increase has made it impossible to gift books to our students and will force me to look elsewhere.

column60: I will not be entering email addresses for my families into your site.  I believe that sharing this kind of personal information without the knowledge of the family is bad practice.  If parents choose to sign up and order books, that is their choice.  My parents are concerned about who has their information and asking permission makes more work for me.  I use my physical flyers as part of my class "homework." I ask parents to sit with their children and look through the flyer and look for books their child is excited about.  They can choose to order from Scholastic or look for them at the library.  I believe they physical flyers are an important part of the process.  They foster parent/child interactions as they sit and look at the flyer together, they help the parent better understand the interests of their child, and they help children understand the concept of ordering something from a physical catalog not just from a screen.

column60: I was surprised to see the limited number of selections available in the first Scholastic flyer!  I was hoping to see more timeless literature titles and authors.  Where are the award winners, both new and old?  Children may choose pop culture titles, but parents are going to actually purchase books that they remember reading as children.  They will be more likely to buy a book that they remember as being a great story or one that someone special to them read to them as a child than a title they know nothing about.  I am having a harder and harder time selling the idea that parents can purchase high quality children's literature from Scholastic. I have been a Golden Apple teacher for many years, and I am not sure how much longer I will continue.

column60: I would like to offer my insights as a long time Golden Apple classroom teacher on the roll out of the new Scholastic book clubs site.  I was very disappointed with the way the new changes were rolled out.  I discovered the changes simply by trying to change the due date of my "September" class order.  When I discovered that I could not change the due date of my order, I had to go looking for the rest of the new changes.  I had already printed my letter to the parents which will now have to be wastefully discarded.  A more prominent letter or email notification that this kind of change was being made would have been appreciated.  The start of school is hard enough without having to make changes to routine and regular systems without warning.  I did consider just trying to spend my 120K+ bonus points and throwing the flyers away.

column60: I would like the ability to delete multiple items from My Wishlist without refreshing my screen after every deletion. column60: I have been a teaching for 15 years and have always LOVED offering Scholastic books clubs for my student to order.  I even have gotten my students sponsored each year so that EVERY student gets a book with each monthly order.  I am about to place my order for the first time this year and to say I am disappointed with the prices and selection options is a vast understatment.  I understand that prices have gone up but when the cheapest book in a book order is 4.99 you are elimanting the affordability that has so often spearheaded orders.  I used to also get 2-3 different types of flyers to send home and each flyer had at least 4 pages of books to look through...now we get 1 flyer and it is single paged.      The cost to teachers is great in many areas but you have now made it to so that the inspiring students to read comes 100% down to money.  That is incredibly sad and disappointing.      I don't know what the fix is but this is NOT the Scholastic I have come to expect!!!

I like to provide my whole class with a book a month.  It is going to be impossible to do that if I have to pay $3-$5 per book with a class of 21 students.

column60: Man oh man...there are many disappointments with Scholastic!     Why are the prices so dang high?  And the excuse of "higher quality books" doesn't shake it when people are priced out of buying books!!!      I myself am using other sources to buy books for myself and for my scholars. I have my friends and family donate monies to my class so they have a free book to take home each month. I cannot use this resource to buy those books because they are too far overpriced.    Where are the Dollar Books?  Where is the opportunity to  go to the Teachers Dollar Store to get even MORE books for our scholars?    Isn't the goal to get quality book titles into the scholars' hands  so they can READ??????    My rating to recommend Scholastic to a colleague is MUCH lower because of the concerns I have scribed above.  The site is not catering to the scholars and their families!!!      ***************************************************************************************************    On a TEACHERS'

column60: Just curious. but why are the flyers different this year and the prices changed? I work with a lot of low income families in a school with a high percentage of English Learners. The flyers now will not work with my families and I will probably never get any orders. My students used to love getting the flyers since they could manage to try and find a dollar or two and be able to buy a book. Usually their parents wouldn't give them money for the order. I used to love that Scholastic made buying books accessible to all children, but this is awful. I am an EL teacher and most of my families speak Spanish. My families will not order books online. They never have and I can guarantee that never will. My students used to try and find money however they could to get something out of the order and their excitement was infectious. Thank you for ruining the joy that a book box could bring.
